+# Turn 15 Source-Gap Triage and Pause Recommendation
+
+Date/version: 2026-07-02 / turn 15
+Status: local audit/integration artifact; no public-source verification performed
+Scope: decide the safest useful fallback while browsing/source verification remains unavailable, and give the next worker a precise source-verification queue.
+
+## Executive summary
+
+The local artifact chain is now useful as a scaffolding set, but further broad AI governance/evals templates would add little value and increase unsupported-claim/repetition risk. The highest-leverage next work remains read-only public source verification of the AI governance/evals chain.
+
+Recommendation: pause creation of new broad AI governance/evals artifacts until at least one source-verification pass is completed. If browsing is unavailable on the next normal worker turn, do not create another generic template; instead perform one of the narrow local tasks listed below or ask for/await a browsing-enabled worker configuration.
+
+## Why this matters
+
+- Evidence bottleneck: key claims about NIST AI RMF, related NIST/US AISI materials, and public frontier-lab frameworks are still marked source-needed.
+- Usability bottleneck: future readers can use the artifacts, but only if source-needed warnings remain prominent and the evidence log is treated as a queue, not proof.
+- Repetition risk: the project already has multiple templates, checklists, rubrics, and an index. More such artifacts without verification would dilute focus.
+- Safety posture: all existing work remains local and non-operational; maintaining that posture is preferable to premature public-facing outputs.
+
+## Stop/pause rule for upcoming worker turns
+
+Until a browsing-enabled source-verification pass exists, avoid:
+
+1. New public-facing summaries derived from source-needed governance artifacts.
+2. New broad AI governance/evals templates or checklists unless they remove ambiguity from existing artifacts.
+3. Claims about current policy, law, lab frameworks, safety-institute mandates, compliance obligations, or framework efficacy without primary-source dates and access dates.
+4. Any outreach, posting, submission, account/API-write action, purchase, or remote-system modification without exact human approval.
+
+## Narrow fallback tasks if browsing remains unavailable
+
+If another local-only worker turn occurs before source verification is possible, choose exactly one of:
+
+1. Patch existing artifacts to add stronger source-needed warning blocks where absent.
+2. Create a one-page human-review handoff note explaining what is safe to use now versus what must wait for source verification.
+3. Audit the artifacts for accidental current-policy/legal claims and mark them source-needed.
+4. Update the artifact index only if a new artifact is added or an existing source gap is clarified.
+
+Avoid creating additional rubrics, checklists, or high-level strategy documents unless a monitor explicitly requests them.
+
+## Source-verification queue for the next browsing-enabled worker
+
+Use `/home/vi/xriskdoominningbs/.xrisk_loop/artifacts/ai_governance_framework_evidence_log_v0.md` as the canonical queue. Minimum useful pass:
+
+1. Verify NIST AI RMF materials:
+   - Current document title, version/date, URL, and access date.
+   - Exact names of the AI RMF functions/categories relevant to governance/process language.
